default&#xa0;defaultBACKGROUND TRENDSdefault&#xa0;
defaultBritish campuses are generally places where Jewish students feel safe to study and do not 
defaultsuffer 
defaultantisemitism on a daily basis. However, 
defaultthere are occasions at some Universities and Students’ Unions when Jewish
default students have been exposed to hate preachers, 
defaultextremist
default groups, radicalised individuals
default, disruption of Jewish Society events and even 
defaultdirect incidents of antisemitism.
default Extremist activity can leave students from a range of minorities feeling vulnerable and reluctant to express their identity openly. Antisemitism, when it occurs, often takes place in a context that includes other forms of bigotry and as such targets all minority students, and therefore the student body as a whole. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThis academic year (2012-13) has seen an increase in far right activity on campus. Some of this increase
default is part of a cycle of extremism between far right and Islamist extremists
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;defaultISLAMIST SPEAKERS:default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultAl-Haddad is the chairman of 
defaultLondon’s 
defaultMuslim Research and Development Foundation, a
default group 
defaultthat gives Sharia advice on financial matters.
default 
defaultAl-Haddad has been embroiled in controversy surrounding comments allegedly made in 2001 where it is alleged that he claimed Jews 
default“a
defaultre the enemies of God and descendants of apes and pigs”.
default 
defaultHe has persistent
defaultly denied making those comments.
default An English-language article by Al-Haddad opposes the actions of Al Qaeda but explains that regardless of what Osama bin Laden did, or did not do, “
defaultit is an established part of our Islamic 
defaultcreed that every Muslim, unlike the disbelievers, will eventually enter paradise
default”. The article also shows various perspectives on what constitutes a “martyr” in combat between Muslims and non-Muslims
default.
default Speaking in English, Al-Haddad may be seen on youtube, discussing “why marriages fail”. This includes his saying that no outsider should ask a husband why he is beating his wife, because such matters should be sorted between the couple.
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultIn February 2010, Tamimi was a speaker at the Federation of Student Islamic Society (FOSIS) Palestine Conference
default held at Manchester University, an Islamic Society event at Cambridge
default and a Palestinian Society event at SOAS.
default During his address to SOAS students, Tamimi called for the destruction of Israel and stated,
default“Today Hamas is considered a terrorist organisation because that’s what the Americans and Israelis and cowardly politicians of Europe want, but what is so terrorist about it? 
default“You shouldn’t be afraid of being labelled extreme, radical or terrorist. If fighting for your home land is terrorism, I take pride in being a terrorist. The Koran tells me if I die for my homeland, I’m a martyr and I long to be a martyr.”
default.
defaultIn November 2004, Tamimi told the BBC’s 
defaultHardtalk
default: 
default&#xa0;
default“If I can go to 
defaultPalestine
default and sacrifice myself I would do it. Why not?...sacrificing myself for 
defaultPalestine
default is a noble cause. It is the straight way to pleasing my God and I would
default do it if I had the opportunity
default”
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultUthman Lateefdefault is a preacher from the Hittin Institute.
default Lateef 
defaultis alleged to have said, “we don’t accept homosexuality...we hate it because Allan hates it”.
default 
defaultIn January and June 2009, Lateef 
defaultwas an advertised speaker 
defaultat events where Anwar Al-Awlaki 
default(a senior Al-Qaeda figure, later killed by a US drone strike) 
defaultgave presentations via video link.
