defaultMuslim Public Affairs Committee:default&#xa0;
defaultThe Muslim Public Affairs Committee (MPAC) 
defaultwebsite includes anti-Zionist conspiracy theorising. 
defaultIn 2006
default, 
defaultAs
defaultgh
defaultar Bukhari, a found
defaulter
default of MPAC and its spokesman, 
defaultwas shown to have 
defaultgiven money to 
defaultHolocaust revisionist, 
defaultDavid Irving in 2000
default;
default and 
defaulturged others to do likewise
default.
default Bukhari stated this was because he had regarded Irving as “anti-Zionist”. In 2004, the National Union of Students described MPAC as antisemitic and banned the group.
default&#xa0;
defaultFollowing the presence of MPAC at Middlesex University, the Students’ Union held a referendum to reaffirm the Union’s policy of not providing a platform for individuals with racist or fascist views (26
defaultth
default-27
defaultth
default February 2013) which received 73% voting yes.
